1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:13,571
This walks through a hybrid AI trial-operations layer — an agentic system, built on the Claude-plus-local stack, that handles the project management, trial management, and monitoring work across a study.

2
00:00:13,871 --> 00:00:25,977
Seventy-five automations: recurrent QC checks, document and SOP ingestion, eTMF filing, Smartsheet timeline updates, and risk-based monitoring.

3
00:00:26,277 --> 00:00:36,124
And one principle holds throughout: the AI drafts, triages, and routes; validated tools and humans own every regulated number and record.

4
00:00:37,124 --> 00:00:39,348
Trial operations are fragmented.

5
00:00:39,648 --> 00:00:57,770
The knowledge and the work are spread across the EDC, the eTMF, Smartsheet, Pinnacle 21, email, and a dozen SOPs — and the team spends its time on manual QC triage, document filing, status decks, and chasing action items.

6
00:00:58,070 --> 00:01:07,349
It is exactly the kind of repetitive, cross-system busywork that an AI layer can absorb — if, and only if, it is governed properly.

7
00:01:08,349 --> 00:01:11,355
So we point the hybrid stack at operations.

8
00:01:11,655 --> 00:01:19,511
Seventy-five governed agents, each one routed by data sensitivity, tiered by risk, and gated by a human.

9
00:01:19,811 --> 00:01:35,112
The AI reads your systems, reasons over de-identified text on Claude or sensitive data on the local model, and proposes a change — but nothing regulated moves until a person approves it, with a full Part 11 audit trail.

10
00:01:36,112 --> 00:01:37,601
Here is how it is wired.

11
00:01:37,901 --> 00:01:41,851
An orchestrator fires agents on a schedule or on study events.

12
00:01:42,151 --> 00:01:52,939
Every agent calls one gateway, which routes by data classification, runs the Presidio guardrail that blocks patient data from the cloud, and logs everything.

13
00:01:53,239 --> 00:02:04,339
Behind it sit three things: the local model for sensitive data, the Claude API for de-identified reasoning, and a RAG knowledge base of your SOPs and study docs.

14
00:02:04,639 --> 00:02:07,419
Connectors expose your systems as tools.

15
00:02:07,719 --> 00:02:12,528
And every regulated change lands in a human-approval queue before it is written.

16
00:02:13,528 --> 00:02:15,431
The governance is the whole point.

17
00:02:15,731 --> 00:02:34,279
Three tiers: green for drafts and cited answers; amber for triage and proposed changes with a human verify; red for anything touching a reported number, a record of truth, or unblinded data — where a validated tool and a human decide, and the model is out of the path.

18
00:02:34,579 --> 00:02:46,568
Three hard rules: patient data never leaves the local model; every reported number comes from a validated tool; and a human approves every change to a regulated record or timeline.

19
00:02:47,568 --> 00:02:49,154
Take project management.

20
00:02:49,454 --> 00:03:03,875
When a data cut is declared, an agent recomputes the critical path in Smartsheet, sees what is now driving the finish date, drafts the you-are-now-blocked notifications, and posts the recomputed plan to the approval queue.

21
00:03:04,175 --> 00:03:12,696
Smartsheet's engine does the math; the AI explains and proposes; the project manager approves before any committed date is written.

22
00:03:12,996 --> 00:03:17,271
And the weekly status report drafts itself from the plan of record.

23
00:03:18,271 --> 00:03:31,113
On documents: agents auto-classify incoming files to the TMF Reference Model, flag missing or expiring documents, and propose filings, which the document controller approves.

24
00:03:31,413 --> 00:03:45,417
And every approved SOP and work instruction is ingested into the knowledge base — so anyone can ask, what does our SOP require for a derived-variable spec, and get the exact clause, cited.

25
00:03:46,417 --> 00:03:51,432
This is the marquee one — recurrent data-validity QC at every stage.

26
00:03:51,731 --> 00:03:59,284
Each night, after a new dataset build, Pinnacle 21 produces the authoritative conformance findings.

27
00:03:59,584 --> 00:04:12,598
The local agent then clusters them, diffs against the last clean run to surface only what is genuinely new, drafts a disposition grounded in the reviewer guides, and routes each one to the right programmer.

28
00:04:12,898 --> 00:04:14,700
It never changes a verdict.

29
00:04:15,000 --> 00:04:20,273
A four-hour manual triage becomes a clean, pre-explained queue at eight a.m.

30
00:04:21,273 --> 00:04:42,256
For monitoring, under ICH E6(R3) risk-based quality management: agents watch the key risk indicators and quality tolerance limits, detect breaches and central-monitoring signals like site outliers or enrollment anomalies, surveil protocol deviations, and assemble the DSMB packet.

31
00:04:42,556 --> 00:04:49,802
Unblinded signals run on the local model; the reported safety numbers come from validated tools with medical review.

32
00:04:50,802 --> 00:04:54,961
Every agent follows the same loop, and it is worth seeing once.

33
00:04:55,261 --> 00:05:17,578
A trigger fires; the agent gathers context from your systems and the cited knowledge base; it classifies the data and routes to local or cloud; it drafts, triages, or summarizes; it proposes the change to the human queue with its rationale and sources; and only on approval is anything written to the system of record — all of it logged.

34
00:05:17,878 --> 00:05:22,820
That loop is what makes seventy-five different automations safe and consistent.

35
00:05:23,820 --> 00:05:26,792
You build it in stages, and you start small.

36
00:05:27,092 --> 00:05:34,739
Phase zero is the stack — gateway, local model, Claude under a BAA, the guardrail and the approval queue.

37
00:05:35,039 --> 00:05:44,892
Phase one is the knowledge base — ingest the SOPs and ship the compliance Q&A agent first; it is pure green, cited, and instantly useful.

38
00:05:45,192 --> 00:05:50,656
Phase two adds read-only connectors and the nightly QC-triage and weekly status agents.

39
00:05:50,956 --> 00:05:55,562
Phase three turns on the event-driven automations and the monitoring signals.

40
00:05:55,862 --> 00:05:59,346
Each agent earns lighter review as it builds a track record.

41
00:06:00,346 --> 00:06:02,543
A day in the layer: at two a.m.

42
00:06:02,843 --> 00:06:09,320
the QC agent surfaces three genuinely new findings among two hundred forty and pre-triages the rest.

43
00:06:09,620 --> 00:06:14,452
At ten-thirty a data cut fires and the timeline cascade updates in minutes.

44
00:06:14,752 --> 00:06:15,892
At one p.m.

45
00:06:16,192 --> 00:06:20,315
a key risk indicator breaches and the signal is drafted for the monitor.

46
00:06:20,615 --> 00:06:29,987
At three, a programmer gets an SOP answer, cited, in seconds, and three documents are filed to the eTMF on approval.

47
00:06:30,287 --> 00:06:34,190
At four, the weekly status report drafts itself.

48
00:06:34,490 --> 00:06:43,142
Every regulated number came from a validated system; no patient data left the building; a human approved every committed change.

49
00:06:44,142 --> 00:06:46,195
So that is the operations layer.

50
00:06:46,495 --> 00:06:56,909
Seventy-five governed automations on the hybrid stack, absorbing the cross-system busywork while validated tools and humans keep ownership of everything that is regulated.

51
00:06:57,209 --> 00:07:05,219
Start with the knowledge base and the SOP agent, keep everything behind the approval queue, and expand as trust grows.

52
00:07:05,519 --> 00:07:15,212
The full catalog — every automation, its engine, its integration, and its human checkpoint — is in the operating wiki alongside this.

53
00:07:15,512 --> 00:07:16,367
Thank you.
